{
  "texts": [
    "There is no consensus on how to estimate the mean returns, and the literature is vast.",
    "Regularization methods can improve mean estimates.",
    "As an example, the Black-Litterman model [BL90] allows a portfolio manager to incorporate her views on how the expected returns differ from the market consensus, and in essence acts as a form of regularization of the portfolio toward the market portfolio.",
    "Another method that serves implicitly as regularization is winsorization, where the mean estimates are clipped when they go outside a specified range [WZ07], [GK00, Chap. 14 ].",
    "Yet another method is cross-sectionalization, where the preliminary estimate of returns µ is replaced with μ, the same values monotonically mapped to (approximately) a Gaussian distribution [GK00, Chap. 14]."
  ]
}